{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535553"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:57:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:57:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15487"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15487"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.05,0.47,0.29,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89957"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8178"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15487"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74116"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"124"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"8966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30640"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89957"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of intermittent numbness and tingling in his fingers, particularly when exposed to cold. He also reports occasional white discolouration of his fingertips followed by redness and pain on rewarming. He works as a construction worker and regularly uses pneumatic drills and sanders for four to six hours per day. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is reduced sensation to light touch and temperature in the fingers of both hands. Allen\u0027s test is normal, and there are no skin changes or ulceration present.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence aspirin","Refer for cervical spine imaging","Arrange workplace modification of vibrating tool use","Prescribe calcium channel blockers","Request nerve conduction studies"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classical features of hand-arm vibration syndrome (HAVS), which develops after prolonged exposure to vibrating tools. The condition manifests with vascular symptoms (similar to Raynaud phenomenon), sensory changes, and musculoskeletal problems. The combination of occupational exposure history and typical symptoms makes this diagnosis likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging workplace modification of vibrating tool use\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step in management. This might include limiting exposure time, using tools with vibration-dampening features, ensuring proper maintenance of equipment, and wearing appropriate protective equipment. Without addressing the underlying cause, the condition will continue to progress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing calcium channel blockers\u003C/strong\u003E may help manage vasospastic symptoms but would not address the underlying cause. These medications should be considered as an adjunct to workplace modifications if symptoms persist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E might be helpful in documenting the extent of nerve damage but would not change the immediate management plan, which should focus on preventing further exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence aspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for HAVS as the condition is not caused by thrombosis but rather by vasospasm and nerve damage from vibration exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical spine imaging\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if there were symptoms or signs suggesting cervical radiculopathy. The bilateral nature of symptoms and clear occupational exposure make HAVS more likely than a cervical spine problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention is crucial in HAVS, and early recognition allows for workplace modifications before permanent damage occurs. The condition is reportable in many jurisdictions as an occupational disease, and affected workers should be referred to occupational health services for ongoing monitoring and management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hand-arm vibration syndrome typically develops after prolonged exposure to vibrating tools, with symptoms including vasospasm, sensory changes, and musculoskeletal problems.","Early recognition and workplace modifications are essential to prevent progression of hand-arm vibration syndrome.","Raynaud phenomenon in young workers using vibrating tools should prompt consideration of occupational exposure."],"references":["Campbell RA, Janko MR, Hacker RI. Hand-arm vibration syndrome: A rarely seen diagnosis. Journal of Vascular Surgery Cases and Innovative Techniques [Internet]. 2017 Jun;3(2):60\u20132. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5757815/","\u200cFalknier S. Diagnosis and treatment of hand-arm vibration syndrome. Clinical Practice: Clinical Update, RACGP [Internet]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/1904b95b-9d4d-43f2-8bed-87c2bd49f485/attachment.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74116"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15487"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74116"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T14:40:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T14:40:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8178"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89957"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i